enTree()` the local tree → flat map\\n2. `FlattenTree()` the remote tree → flat map  \\n3. Merge maps (remote entries overwrite local on collision)\\n4. `BuildTreeFromEntries()` rebuilds entire tree\\n\\n**Cost: O(total files across both trees)**, but it only runs once (not per-commit).\\n\\n## The \\\"Better\\\" Approach: `WriteCommitted` (tree surgery)\\n\\n`WriteCommitted` in `committed.go` uses **`UpdateSubtree`** from `parse_tree.go`:\\n\\n1. `getSessionsBranchRef()` — gets root tree hash in O(1)\\n2. `flattenCheckpointEntries()` — reads **only** the target checkpoint's subtree, not the whole tree\\n3. Builds the checkpoint subtree from the small set of entries\\n4. `UpdateSubtree()` — **walks only the path segments** (`[\\\"a3\\\"]` → `\\\"b2c4d5e6f7\\\"`) replacing just the modified subtree hashes at each level, keeping all sibling entries untouched\\n\\n**Cost: O(depth of path + files in checkpoint)**. With 10,000 checkpoints, it touches ~3 tree objects (root → shard dir → checkpoint dir) instead of walking all 10,000.\\n\\n## The Key Differences\\n\\n| | Flatten+Rebuild (reconcile & pre-push) | Tree Surgery (WriteCommitted) |\\n|---|---|---|\\n| **Reads** | Entire tree | Only affected path |\\n| **Writes** | Rebuilds all tree objects | Rebuilds only path from leaf to root |\\n| **Scaling** | O(N) where N = total files | O(d) where d = tree depth |\\n| **Sibling trees** | Re-read and re-hashed | Keep existing hashes |\\n\\n## Why It Matters (and When It Doesn't)\\n\\n**Pre-push merge**: Runs once, only when local/remote diverge. The full flatten is acceptable because it's a rare operation and merging two diverged trees inherently requires seeing everything.\\n\\n**Your reconcile**: Runs `FlattenTree` 3 times *per commit* being cherry-picked. If someone has 50 local commits and 500 checkpoints on the remote, that's 150 full tree walks. With the sharded structure (`a3/b2c4d5e6f7/` with files inside), the tree is deep and branchy — flattening is expensive.\\n\\n**WriteCommitted**: Uses `UpdateSubtree` because it runs on *every commit the user makes* (hot path in PostCommit hook). It needs to be fast even with thousands of existing checkpoints.\\n\\n## What You Could Improve in Reconcile\\n\\nYour cherry-pick could use `ApplyTreeChanges` (from `parse_tree.go:197`) instead of flatten+rebuild. It takes a list of `TreeChange` structs (path + entry) and applies them in a single recursive pass, only touching modified subtrees:\\n\\n```go\\n// Instead of: flatten tip → merge → BuildTreeFromEntries\\n// Use: ApplyTreeChanges(repo, tipTreeHash, changes)\\n```\\n\\nThis would make each cherry-pick O(changed files * tree depth) instead of O(total files).\\n\\nThat said, reconciliation is a rare one-time repair operation, so the performance difference may not matter in practice.\"}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":1,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":218,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":71049,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":218},\"output_tokens\":5,\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"inference_geo\":\"not_available\"}},\"requestId\":\"req_011CYdkiwrPPnGyUcG61MxUQ\",\"type\":\"assistant\",\"uuid\":\"09c4408a-2a07-428b-a7fd-10b1689d1c5d\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-02T06:09:26.562Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"09c4408a-2a07-428b-a7fd-10b1689d1c5d\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/dvydra/src/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"cd762943-7b84-42bd-8e4a-de65cbab4227\",\"version\":\"2.1.63\",\"gitBranch\":\"main\",\"slug\":\"tender-juggling-tarjan\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_01HjrupPpfN76hPrdekbPwkg\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"tool_use\",\"id\":\"toolu_013Dvyq3qT1egjbgBcYUqBsR\",\"name\":\"AskUserQuestion\",\"input\":{\"questions\":[{\"question\":\"Would you like me to plan refactoring the reconcile cherry-pick to use ApplyTreeChanges/UpdateSubtree for consistency and better scaling,