using `FlattenTree` + `BuildTreeFromEntries` (the flatten+rebuild approach):**\\n2. **`cherryPickOnto`** in `strategy/metadata_reconcile.go` (on the `fix/reconcile-disconnected-metadata-branch` branch) -- flattens commit tree, parent tree, and tip tree to compute and apply deltas. Runs once ever (one-time repair).\\n3. **`fetchAndMergeSessionsCommon`** in `strategy/push_common.go` -- flattens local and remote trees, unions them, rebuilds. Runs rarely (only on push with diverged histories).\\n\\nThere is also:\\n4. **`DeleteOrphanedCheckpoints`** in `strategy/cleanup.go` -- flattens the metadata branch tree, deletes entries by prefix, rebuilds. Runs rarely (manual cleanup command).\\n\\nAnd there is a **fourth primitive** (`UpdateSubtree`) used by `WriteCommitted` in `checkpoint/committed.go`, which is a subtree-replacement operation (not file-level changes). This is already efficient and different in nature from the others.\\n\\n### Analysis: Can All Three Use `ApplyTreeChanges`?\\n\\n**Yes**, all three flatten+rebuild sites can be converted to use `ApplyTreeChanges`. The key insight is that in each case, you still need to flatten trees to **compute** the delta (what changed), but you no longer need to flatten the **target tree** just to apply changes to it. `ApplyTreeChanges` accepts changes as `[]TreeChange` and surgically applies them.\\n\\nLet me analyze each:\\n\\n#### 1. `cherryPickOnto` (reconcile)\\n\\nCurrent approach:\\n- Flatten commit tree -> `commitEntries`\\n- Flatten parent tree -> `parentEntries`\\n- Diff those two to get `added` and `deleted`\\n- Flatten tip tree -> `mergedEntries` (this is the wasteful step)\\n- Apply adds/deletes to `mergedEntries`\\n- `BuildTreeFromEntries(mergedEntries)` (this is the wasteful step)\\n\\nProposed approach:\\n- Flatten commit tree -> `commitEntries` (still needed to compute delta)\\n- Flatten parent tree -> `parentEntries` (still needed to compute delta)\\n- Diff those two to get `added` and `deleted`\\n- Convert to `[]TreeChange` and call `ApplyTreeChanges(tipTree, changes)`\\n\\nThis eliminates flattening the tip tree and rebuilding it from scratch. The delta computation (commit vs parent) still requires flattening both, which is unavoidable.\\n\\n#### 2. `fetchAndMergeSessionsCommon` (pre-push merge)\\n\\nCurrent approach:\\n- Flatten local tree -> `entries`\\n- Flatten remote tree -> `entries` (overwrites on collision; remote wins)\\n- `BuildTreeFromEntries(entries)`\\n\\nThis is a true union where remote entries overwrite local on collision. To express this as `ApplyTreeChanges`, pick one tree as the base and compute what the other tree adds/modifies. Since we want remote-wins semantics, the natural choice is: use the local tree as base, compute what remote adds or differs, and apply those as changes.\\n\\nProposed approach:\\n- Flatten local tree -> `localEntries`\\n- Flatten remote tree -> `remoteEntries`\\n- Compute diff: for each entry in `remoteEntries`, if it differs from or is absent in `localEntries`, add it as a `TreeChange`\\n- Call `ApplyTreeChanges(localTreeHash, changes)`\\n\\nThis still requires flattening both trees (unavoidable for a union), but avoids rebuilding the entire merged tree from scratch. The savings are modest for the metadata branch (small tree), but it unifies the approach.\\n\\n#### 3. `DeleteOrphanedCheckpoints` (cleanup)\\n\\nCurrent approach:\\n- Flatten entire metadata tree\\n- Delete entries by checkpoint path prefix\\n- `BuildTreeFromEntries`\\n\\nProposed approach:\\n- Still need to flatten to find which paths exist under each checkpoint prefix\\n- But can construct `[]TreeChange` with nil entries (deletions) and call `ApplyTreeChanges`\\n\\nAlternative: Since deletions are always at known shard paths like `a3/b2c4d5e6f7/`, you could use `UpdateSubtree` to replace the shard directory without that checkpoint. But `ApplyTreeChanges` with nil entries is simpler and consistent.\\n\\n### Recommended Approach: Introduce a Helper Function\\n\\nRather than just mechanically replacing each call site, introduce a thin helper that wraps the common pattern of \\\"diff two flat maps, produce `[]TreeChange`\\\":\\n\\n```go\\n// DiffTrees computes the tree changes needed to transform a tree matching\\n// `base` entries into one matching `target` entries. Returns changes suitable\\n// for ApplyTreeChanges.\\n//\\n// For entries present in target but absent/different in base: add/modify.\\n// For entries present in base but absent in target: delete.\\nfunc DiffTrees(base, target map[string]object.TreeEntry) []TreeChange\\n```\\n\\nThis helper would live in `checkpoint/parse_tree.go` alongside `ApplyTreeChanges` and `TreeChange`. It captures the shared pattern: compute what changed between two flat entry maps.\\n\\nEach call site then becomes:\\n1. Flatten the trees you need to compare.\\n2. Call `DiffTrees(base, target)` to get `[]TreeChange`.\\n3. Call `ApplyTreeChanges(tipTreeHash, changes)` to apply them.\\n\\n### Detailed Changes Per Call Site\\n\\n#### A. `cherryPickOnto` in `strategy/metadata_reconcile.go`\\n\\n**Before:**\\n```go\\n// Flatten 3 trees, manipulate map, BuildTreeFromEntries\\ncommitEntries := flatten(commitTree)\\nparentEntries := flatten(parentTree)\\n// compute added/deleted\\nmergedEntries := flatten(tipTree)     // <-- eliminated\\n// apply adds/deletes to mergedEntries\\nBuildTreeFromEntries(mergedEntries)   // <-- eliminated\\n```\\n\\n**After:**\\n```go\\ncommitEntries := flatten(commitTree)\\nparentEntries := flatten(parentTree)\\nchanges := checkpoint.DiffTrees(parentEntries, commitEntries)\\nif len(changes) == 0 { continue }\\ntipCommit, _ := repo.CommitObject(currentTip)\\nmergedTreeHash, _ := checkpoint.ApplyTreeChanges(repo, tipCommit.TreeHash, changes)\\n```\\n\\nThe third flatten (tip tree) and `BuildTreeFromEntries` are both eliminated. Two flattens remain (commit and parent) because they are needed to compute the delta.\\n\\n#### B. `fetchAndMergeSessionsCommon` in `strate