mEntries` to build fixture trees from scratch — that's the right tool for construction (vs modification)\\n- Keep `FlattenTree` and `BuildTreeFromEntries` exported — they're still needed for reading trees and for test fixtures\\n\\n## Branch\\n\\nCreate a new branch `refactor/unify-tree-operations` from `main` for these changes.\\n\\n## Verification\\n\\n1. `mise run fmt && mise run lint && mise run test:ci`\\n2. The existing `tree_surgery_equiv_test.go` pattern should be extended: for each converted call site, add a test that verifies the new `ApplyTreeChanges` path produces the same tree hash as the old `FlattenTree` + `BuildTreeFromEntries` path\\n\",\"tool_use_id\":\"toolu_01DEtYUx2BHiGfkeFT9sdgnG\"}]},\"uuid\":\"a7587f5f-f69d-49dd-acf9-0d6f46dcbd7d\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-02T06:23:58.603Z\",\"toolUseResult\":{\"plan\":\"# Unify Tree Modification to Use `ApplyTreeChanges`\\n\\n## Context\\n\\nThere are three production call sites that modify git trees using the flatten+rebuild approach (`FlattenTree` + `BuildTreeFromEntries`), while a fourth (`WriteCommitted`) uses the surgical approach (`UpdateSubtree`/`ApplyTreeChanges`). These are all doing the same logical operation — \\\"modify entries in a git tree\\\" — but with two completely different implementations that produce identical results. Consolidating on a single primitive (`ApplyTreeChanges`) reduces cognitive overhead and makes the codebase consistent.\\n\\n## Changes\\n\\n### 1. Add `DiffTrees` helper to `checkpoint/parse_tree.go`\\n\\nA pure function that computes `[]TreeChange` from two flat entry maps:\\n\\n```go\\nfunc DiffTrees(base, target map[string]object.TreeEntry) []TreeChange\\n```\\n\\n- Entries in target but absent/different in base → add/modify (`TreeChange` with non-nil Entry)\\n- Entries in base but absent in target → delete (`TreeChange` with nil Entry)\\n- Add unit tests in `parse_tree_test.go`\\n\\n### 2. Convert `cherryPickOnto` in `strategy/metadata_reconcile.go`\\n\\n**Before**: Fla